    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Search visibility</strong> is a percentage score estimating how much of all available organic clicks a site captures across its tracked keywords. A site ranking first for every tracked keyword would score 100%; a site with no rankings scores 0%. According to Sistrix data, <strong>the average website has less than 3% search visibility</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Average score</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Under 3%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Position 1 CTR</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~27%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Individual keyword rankings move daily. Search visibility smooths those fluctuations into a single trend line you can actually report on and act from. It is the equivalent of a stock price for SEO — not the full story, but the most useful single number for tracking progress.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is search visibility?</h2>
        <p>Search visibility is a composite metric calculated by SEO tools (Semrush, Sistrix, Ahrefs, Moz) to estimate the share of available organic clicks a site is capturing across its keyword set.</p>
        <p>The calculation works by weighting each keyword by its search volume and the click-through rate for its current ranking position, then expressing the result as a percentage of the maximum possible clicks:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Position 1 receives approximately 27% CTR</li>
          <li>Position 2 receives approximately 15% CTR</li>
          <li>Position 5 receives approximately 7% CTR</li>
          <li>Position 10 receives approximately 2.5% CTR</li>
          <li>Position 11+ receives under 1% CTR</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Each tool uses slightly different CTR curves and data sources, so visibility scores are not comparable across platforms. Use one tool consistently and track the trend, not the absolute number.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Benchmark context</div>
          <p>Sistrix data shows the average website has search visibility below 3%. Most real-world sites fall between 1-30%. What matters is the trend over time and your position relative to direct competitors — not hitting an arbitrary absolute benchmark.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why search visibility matters for SEO reporting</h2>
        <p>Search visibility solves a real problem with keyword-level tracking: individual rankings fluctuate too much to be reliable day-to-day signals. Here's what visibility adds:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Single health metric.</strong> Instead of reporting on 500 individual keyword positions, one visibility score shows whether the site is moving in the right direction overall.</li>
          <li><strong>Algorithm update detection.</strong> A sudden visibility drop of 20%+ often corresponds with a Google core update. This triggers an investigation before organic traffic numbers confirm the problem.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor benchmarking.</strong> Comparing visibility scores across competitors reveals market position and the scale of the gap to close.</li>
          <li><strong>Long-term progress tracking.</strong> Content and SEO investments take 3-6 months to compound. Visibility shows that compounding in a single trend line.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How search visibility is calculated</h2>
        <p>The underlying formula multiplies each keyword's potential traffic by the site's actual capture rate, sums everything, and divides by maximum possible capture:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Simplified search visibility formula</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">For each keyword:</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;potential_clicks = search_volume × position_ctr<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-label">Total visibility:</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;visibility = sum(potential_clicks) / sum(max_possible_clicks) × 100<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Example: 3 keywords</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"crm software" (10,000/mo, position 3, 10% CTR) = 1,000 clicks<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"best crm" (5,000/mo, position 8, 3% CTR) = 150 clicks<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"crm for startups" (800/mo, position 1, 27% CTR) = 216 clicks<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-label">Max possible:</span> 10,000 + 5,000 + 800 = 15,800<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Actual:</span> 1,000 + 150 + 216 = 1,366<br>
          <span class="uf-new">Visibility = 1,366 / 15,800 × 100 = 8.6%</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Search visibility vs other SEO metrics — which to use?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Metric</th><th>What it measures</th><th>Best for</th><th>Limitation</th></tr>
            </thead>
