        <h2 id="examples">Real search visibility case studies</h2>

        <h3>1. Local plumbing company — 4x visibility growth</h3>
        <p>A plumbing business tracked 75 local keywords starting at 4% search visibility. After 6 months of consistent content publishing and local SEO improvements — Google Business Profile optimization, citation building, 12 new local service pages — they reached 18% visibility. That 4.5x increase translated directly to a measurable increase in phone inquiries from organic search.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS — core update recovery</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company's visibility dropped from 12% to 7% overnight after a Google core update devalued thin, template-driven content. The team audited their 200-page site and identified 40 underperforming pages with under 400 words and no original analysis. Replacing them with in-depth, data-backed articles recovered visibility to 15% within 3 months — 25% above the pre-update baseline.</p>

        <h3>3. Ecommerce — keyword set selection effect</h3>
        <p>An ecommerce site tracking 50 branded keywords showed 45% visibility. When they expanded tracking to 500 category and competitor keywords, visibility appeared to drop to 8% — but organic traffic hadn't changed. The lesson: visibility scores reflect your keyword selection as much as your actual performance. Always track a representative mix of branded, category, and long-tail terms.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Search visibility vs share of voice — which is more useful?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use search visibility when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Tracking your own progress over time</li>
              <li>Reporting overall SEO health to stakeholders</li>
              <li>Detecting algorithm update impacts early</li>
              <li>Measuring content investment ROI</li>
              <li>Setting quarterly SEO goals</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use share of voice when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Benchmarking against specific competitors</li>
              <li>Understanding your market position</li>
              <li>Justifying competitive content investment</li>
              <li>Presenting to leadership about market share</li>
              <li>Identifying which competitors to study</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for improving search visibility</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Target page-2 keywords first.</strong> Keywords in positions 11-20 are the fastest visibility wins. Moving from position 15 to position 5 produces a larger CTR jump than moving from 5 to 1. Find these in Search Console: queries with impressions but low clicks.</li>
          <li><strong>Track a representative keyword set.</strong> Visibility is only as good as your keyword selection. Include a mix of branded, category, long-tail, and competitor terms — not just the easiest ones you rank for.</li>
          <li><strong>Update underperforming existing content before creating new content.</strong> Improving 10 existing pages that rank on page 2 typically delivers faster visibility gains than publishing 10 new pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Build topical depth, not page breadth.</strong> Google rewards sites with comprehensive coverage of a topic. Publishing 5 deep articles on one subtopic beats 20 thin articles covering 20 different topics.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor visibility alongside organic traffic.</strong> Visibility rising but traffic flat suggests you're gaining rankings for low-volume keywords. Traffic rising but visibility flat suggests untracked keywords are driving growth.</li>
          <li><strong>Benchmark against direct competitors monthly.</strong> Your absolute visibility score matters less than your score relative to the 3-5 sites competing for the same keywords.</li>
          <li><strong>Check visibility after every major Google update.</strong> Core updates can shift visibility by 20%+ in 48 hours. Having a pre-update baseline lets you diagnose the cause and prioritize recovery.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — tracking only keywords you already rank for</div>
          <p>Tracking only keywords where you hold positions 1-10 produces an artificially high visibility score and hides the real size of your opportunity. Always include aspirational keywords — terms where competitors rank but you don't yet — to get an honest read on the gap.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common search visibility mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Comparing visibility scores across different tools.</strong> Semrush, Sistrix, and Ahrefs use different CTR curves and keyword databases. Compare within one tool only.</li>
          <li><strong>Panicking at daily fluctuations.</strong> Visibility moves by 1-3% daily due to normal ranking volatility. Track weekly or monthly averages, not daily numbers.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the keyword set effect.</strong> Adding competitive keywords to your tracking will lower your score even if nothing changed. Document keyword set changes to avoid misreading trends.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating visibility as the only SEO metric.</strong> Visibility is a useful summary metric, but it doesn't tell you which pages are driving business outcomes. Pair it with organic traffic and conversions.</li>
          <li><strong>Not investigating sudden drops.</strong> A 15%+ visibility drop within a week usually signals a real problem — technical issue, manual action, or algorithm impact. Always investigate within 48 hours.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
